### 1.4 — [BOTH VIEWS] Desktop and mobile views both render in the DOM

| Detail | |
|---|---|
| **File** | [layout.css:19-26](file:///c:/Users/josep/Desktop/Resume_Project/Prototype_v2/css/layout.css#L19-L26) |
| **What is broken** | Both desktop and mobile views are present in the DOM simultaneously. The `active` class is hardcoded on `.frame.mobile.view` in every HTML file, and the media queries in layout.css override visibility. This means **on initial load before CSS parses**, the mobile view flashes briefly on desktop. Also, both remain in the DOM bloating memory and allowing duplicate ID conflicts (e.g. multiple `modal-overlay` targets). |
| **Why** | The architecture uses a dual-frame approach (two complete UIs in one page) instead of responsive CSS on a single DOM. The `.view` class hides by default (`display:none`), but `.view.active` shows each, and media queries use `!important` to force visibility. |
| **Fix** | This is architectural. Short-term: remove the hardcoded `active` class from mobile frames and let media queries alone control visibility. The `active` class on `.frame.mobile.view` is overridden by `@media` anyway: |

```diff
 <!-- In every HTML file, change: -->
-<div class="frame mobile view active" id="mobile-view">
+<div class="frame mobile view" id="mobile-view">
```

Since the media queries already use `!important` to control which frame shows, the `active` class on mobile is redundant and causes the flash of unstyled content.

