### 1.5 — [DESKTOP ONLY] Profile page has conflicting flex direction

| Detail | |
|---|---|
| **File** | [profile.html:34](file:///c:/Users/josep/Desktop/Resume_Project/Prototype_v2/profile.html#L34) + [profile.css:2](file:///c:/Users/josep/Desktop/Resume_Project/Prototype_v2/css/profile.css#L2) |
| **What is broken** | CSS `.profile-body` sets `display: flex; gap: 16px` (default `flex-direction: row`). But the inline style on the HTML element overrides with `flex-direction: column`. The CSS also defines `.profile-left` (width:200px) and `.profile-right` (flex:1) which expect a **row** layout. The inline column override makes these width declarations meaningless. |
| **Why** | Inline style `flex-direction:column` conflicts with CSS that was designed for a two-column side-by-side layout. |
| **Fix** | Remove the inline style override and restructure to use the CSS-defined row layout, or update the CSS to match the column intent: |

```diff
 <!-- profile.html line 34 -->
-<div class="profile-body" style="flex-direction:column;gap:16px">
+<div class="profile-body">
```

Then reorganize children to use `.profile-left` and `.profile-right` wrappers per the CSS expectation.

